Do you believe that the product is the marketing?

Product is number one, number two, and number three=E2=80=94and then comes =
everything else. The consumer is so much more educated today than they were=
 in the =E2=80=9980s. I=E2=80=99d also say we are comfort-seekers today. Co=
nsumers have so many more choices today, too. And what drives business more=
 than any endorsement or any form of marketing is actually what consumers a=
re telling each other=E2=80=94and I=E2=80=99m not talking about influencers=
 who are paid. I=E2=80=99m talking about consumers one-to-one. Whenever I=
=E2=80=99ve failed=E2=80=94and I failed many times=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s alw=
ays because the product hasn=E2=80=99t lived up to its promise.

Brick & Mortar, Plus I.P.O. Chatter

As an investor in a luxury brand, what do you think is happening at this po=
int in the cycle of the customer=E2=80=99s relationship with these big labe=
ls?

There are a few things that are converging. For one, it expanded so rapidly=
 over the last four or five years, some pullback is to be expected. Secondl=
y, they=E2=80=99ve really priced themselves out. They felt like they had in=
finite demand, and they raised prices to a degree where it=E2=80=99s just r=
eally hard to stomach for a lot of aspirational customers. And lastly, it=
=E2=80=99s the industrialization of luxury; that plays a huge part.

With Skims, you=E2=80=99ve been slow to open stores. You=E2=80=99ve been ve=
ry careful about the rollout.

It took us so many years to scale the demand we had online, and by the time=
 we started thinking about stores, there was an expectation. If we=E2=80=99=
re opening
a store, it=E2=80=99s got to be different. It=E2=80=99s got to live up to c=
ustomers=E2=80=99 expectations of what a Skims store is. So we spent a lot =
of time conceptualizing that. We then had a test store, a secret store in A=
ustin for a year, which we never publicized.

And it=E2=80=99s been the beauty of the whole Skims project that Kim and I =
have been in control of our business and how we want to build it, and there=
=E2=80=99s always a lot of speculation like, Why don=E2=80=99t you do this?=
 When are you going to go public? We=E2=80=99ve never spoken about going pu=
blic; all I=E2=80=99ve ever said is that at some point we probably will=E2=
=80=94but I=E2=80=99ve never actually spoken about it. With stores, it=E2=
=80=99s kind of the same thing. We did it when we focused our attention on =
it, and we=E2=80=99re perfectly happy with having six stores right now.

We=E2=80=99re still learning. But at the end of next year, there=E2=80=99s =
going to be a hell of a lot more stores.

